subSubSection.paragraph:
Prostomium rounded anteriorly with two dorsoventrally flattened buccal lips and an anterior notch between them (
Fig. 2A, B
). Two palps and three antennae slender and tapering, each with short palpophores and ceratophores arranged in an arc on posterior margin of prostomium.Antennae smooth, of equal length, slightly longer than palps, about 2x longer than prostomium (
Fig. 2A
). Small pair of eyes present, very faint, located at posterior base between palps and lateral antennae (only visible on left side of 
holotype
). First peristomial ring about 2.5–3.0x longer than second one, with rounded notch on anterior margin, ventrally (
Fig. 2B
).

First two parapodia located below middle line of body wall, but gradually positioned dorsally to about midline in subsequent segments (
Fig. 2A, B
). Notopodial dorsal cirri slender, tapering, extending laterally slightly beyond both post-chaetal lobe and ventral cirri in anterior body (
Fig. 3A
); shorter than chaetal lobes in mid-body chaetigers (
Fig. 3B
); and similar size as chaetal lobes in posterior chaetigers (
Fig. 3C
), except for posterior-most (
Fig. 3D
). Chaetal lobes comprising a low pre-chaetal lip and a tongue-like post-chaetal lobe (
Fig. 3A
). Ventral cirri bluntly conical, bases slightly expanded, first few exceeding lengths of post-chaetal lobes, thereafter about same length as post-chaetal lobes (
Fig. 3A, D
). Branchiae pectinate, commencing from chaetiger 48 (22–50), best developed from chaetigers 44–75 to mid-posterior body, and continuing to within 10 chaetigers from pygidium; number of filaments increasing from 1–2 anteriorly to 
5–9 in
mid-body (
Figs 2C
; 
3
B–C), decreasing to 4–5 (6) (
Fig. 3D
) in last several chaetigers. Branchiae wrinkled and vascularised at base where best developed.

Pygidium round, crenulated, dorsally positioned, with one pair of short pygidial cirri attached at ventral edge (
Fig. 2D
).
